After seeing this for the first time back in June 2011, I knew I had to get it. It made me laugh, made me think, it gave my heart a warm- feeling, and most of all, because it was the good, it landed a spot in my top 20 favourite films (well, at the time it was top 30, but now it's 20).

Role Models sees Anson and Danny (portrayed by Seann William Scott and Paul Rudd): Two "friends" that work together selling energy drinks (they promote an energy drink called "Minotaur" to prevent kids from going on to drugs; meaning they encourage them not to do drugs...)

Only after Danny loses his girlfriend, Beth Jones (Elizabeth Banks) does a huge bomb come down on Danny - in which he turns up in an irresponsible manner with Wheeler (Anson - William Scott), at another School - although Wheeler being positive as he loves the job, also seems to be happy and he has his "game-face" on. After the result, Danny and Wheeler come out (Danny is somewhat infuriated and irritated) and they find their Minotaur truck to be towed because of where they had parked it. Danny is unwillingly able to take responsibility here - and as a result, he gets into the truck that's being towed, that is connected to a tow truck, and attempts to drive off; only damaging the tow truck and irresponsibly crashing it (the Minotaur truck) into a statue. 

They're given the option of either prison for 30 days, or 150 hours of community service at "Sturdy Wings" - a place where bigs (adults) are paired with littles (kids) in order to have a fun, enjoyable time, get to know one another, and basically become friends. 

Wheeler is paired with the foul-mouthed kid whose obsession with breasts gets the better of him. Danny is paired up with Augie Farcques - a nerd who gets carried away with live action role-playing games (medieval type ones); specifically called "L.A.I.R.E" which stands for "Live Action Interactive Role-playing Explorers". 

But enough, I have said to much! Off you go, my film-loving acquaintances - enjoy what I believe to be the greatest comedy ever made. It has genuine hilarious scenes, foul-mouth humour, heart-warming melt-scenes and lovable characters that you'll love from the moment you're introduced to them (not literally, but through the magic of the film). Absolutely amazing! 10/10
